      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "d3667523-4ee6-46fb-8b03-9c6f7f9405e7",
        "text": "Unity is marketed to be an all purpose engine, and as a result supports both 2D ([[2D computer graphics]]) and 3D ([[3D computer graphics]]) graphics, drag and drop functionality and scripting through its 3 custom languages. The engine targets the following APIs: Direct3D ([[Microsoft Direct3D]]) and Vulkan ([[Vulkan (API)]]) on Windows and Xbox 360; [[OpenGL]] on Mac, Linux, and Windows; [[OpenGL ES]] on Android and iOS; and proprietary APIs on [[video game console]]s. Within 2D games, Unity allows importation of sprites and an advanced 2D world renderer. For 3D games, Unity allows specification of [[texture compression]] and resolution settings for each platform that the game engine supports,<ref name=\"Unity Multiplatform\" /> and provides support for [[bump mapping]], [[reflection mapping]], [[parallax mapping]], [[screen space ambient occlusion]] (SSAO), dynamic shadows using [[shadow map]]s, render-to-texture ([[Render to Texture]]) and full-screen post-processing effects.[http://docs.unity3d.com/Documentation/Manual/DirectX11.html Using DirectX11 in Unity 4]  Unity also offers services to developers, these are: Unity Ads, Unity Analytics, Unity Certification, Unity Cloud Build, Unity Everyplay, Unity IAP, Unity Multiplayer, Unity Performance Reporting and Unity Collaborate which is in beta."
      },
